So there's a book called Getting Things Done, one of these self-help books about productivity,

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:26.439
and I think most of it is not worth reading. But there is one lesson in there, which is about

00:42:26.439 --> 00:42:31.719
having a- I couldn't even remember the exact name. It was something like a capture-everything device.

00:42:33.159 --> 00:42:38.520
So for me, having the Todoist app both on my phone and on my laptop, chances are,

00:42:38.520 --> 00:42:42.120
whenever I'm around and I think, oh, I need to do this, I just add it to my app.

00:42:42.919 --> 00:42:47.879
And one insight that I got from that book was that it's a major source of stress in your life

00:42:47.879 --> 00:42:52.760
when there's open loops. So that is to say, when there's something that needs doing

00:42:52.760 --> 00:42:57.320
and it's not captured somewhere. Like if you're just about to go to sleep and you think, oh,

00:42:57.320 --> 00:43:02.120
I really need to remember to do this tomorrow. I really need to remember to do that. It's going

00:43:02.120 --> 00:43:05.719
to stress you out. It's going to be very difficult to get to sleep. But if you know that it's in your

00:43:05.719 --> 00:43:10.360
app and the next day you're going to look at your app because that's part of your routine,

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:15.479
that's part of your routine. And there's an app, there's another app. In my case,

00:43:15.479 --> 00:43:21.879
there's another app that charges me money. If I don't regularly look at my Todoist app

00:43:21.879 --> 00:43:30.439
and tick off boxes, then yeah, you're going to look at it. And yeah, in the long run,

00:43:30.439 --> 00:43:36.199
I think this really reduces your stress. So the other app that, if you feel like you don't have

00:43:36.199 --> 00:43:40.439
enough self-control, that you really need an app to charge you money, if you don't stick to your

00:43:40.439 --> 00:43:47.800
goals, then Beeminder is the tool for that. I can see a few people looking like they're writing this.

00:43:49.080 --> 00:43:54.520
That's amazing, Marco. I feel like you hold yourself hostage a lot to get things done.

00:43:55.399 --> 00:44:01.479
It actually reminds me of Nictography, which is what Lewis Carroll, the writer of Alice in

00:44:01.479 --> 00:44:05.959
Wonderland, invented a way to write in the dark so that he could wake up in the middle of the night

00:44:05.959 --> 00:44:11.239
and write things legibly in the dark. Go Google it if you're interested. Nictography is fascinating.

