00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:50.439
Polars, PyArrow. If you could just speak to how Narwhals might work with or be competing with

00:44:50.439 --> 00:44:56.120
some of the work being done with DuckDB and others. Awesome, yeah. I wouldn't consider any of

00:44:56.120 --> 00:45:02.280
those to be our competitors, and I'm not sure that, like for some of them, I wouldn't say that

00:45:02.280 --> 00:45:08.280
the competition is on the interface but on the engine. So let's say Polars versus DuckDB, I think

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:15.320
there is some open competition for who's the fastest, who's the most scalable, and all of that.

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:20.360
But on the interface they are completely different. So the way you interact with DuckDB is by writing

00:45:20.360 --> 00:45:28.360
SQL and Polars has its own API. For Narwhals itself, I'm hoping that we can get to

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:36.120
defining a lazy-only layer of support that we should support DuckDB in. But going back to

00:45:36.120 --> 00:45:41.239
priorities, first we need to get the Plotly integration in. That's the top priority. And

00:45:41.239 --> 00:45:47.080
next year in 2025, when I've got a bit more headspace, I'd really like to focus on doing,

00:45:47.639 --> 00:45:53.639
yeah, on defining the rules behind SQL engines for Narwhals. The main difference that we have there

00:45:53.639 --> 00:45:59.399
that we need to address is that with SQL engines you don't have a defined row order, but in Polars

00:46:00.360 --> 00:46:08.840
and Pandas, the row order is always defined, even if it's a lazy data frame. So I'm going to have to

00:46:10.679 --> 00:46:14.679
figure out what to do about that. Like we've got some methods like a cumulative sum,

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:23.399
a cumulative sum makes sense if your row order is defined, but if you don't have a row order,

00:46:23.399 --> 00:46:27.719
then you need to define what your cumulative sum is ordered by.

00:46:28.840 --> 00:46:33.719
So what we might do is just have like a cumulative sum, which is available in Narwhals,

00:46:33.719 --> 00:46:39.399
and then cumulative sum by, which is also available. But if you want to use the

00:46:40.280 --> 00:46:45.639
lazy only layer, then you have to use cumulative sum by rather than cumulative sum.

