interacting with things. And, you know, as you know, the exposed interfaces potentially have

00:47:41.159 --> 00:47:48.040
different models of how one works with the data. And so over time, it gets confusing. That's why

00:47:48.040 --> 00:47:54.520
I put that XKCD link in there, because now you've added another abstraction layer with another level

00:47:54.520 --> 00:48:00.439
of interfaces that supposedly are going to unify, but in fact just become an additional set of

00:48:00.439 --> 00:48:05.239
things that people have to maintain and manage. And so it wasn't so much of the implementation

00:48:05.239 --> 00:48:12.679
details, but how people actually work with the tooling and the APIs and method calls and

00:48:12.679 --> 00:48:18.120
interfaces that they have to get familiar with in order to be productive in doing the type of

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:26.120
data analysis that they are interested in doing. Yeah. Yeah, it's true that things,

00:48:27.080 --> 00:48:32.439
yeah, I'm familiar with the XKCD comic, the one of the, I've not clicked on the link,

00:48:32.439 --> 00:48:34.760
but I think I know which one you're talking about. The one of that is

00:48:35.399 --> 00:48:40.840
graphical standards in Python. And now there's 15 standards. Yeah, yeah. That's right. Exactly.

00:48:40.840 --> 00:48:46.360
Right. So, yeah, so my vision with Narwhals isn't that this brings everything together.

00:48:46.919 --> 00:48:53.080
It's, my vision isn't that users will use this. I think users should use, learn the best task for

00:48:53.080 --> 00:48:59.479
their, use the best tool for their task, which nowadays for most data related tasks, I think,

00:48:59.479 --> 00:49:05.159
is probably going to be either Polars or DuckDB. I really recommend learning both, to be honest.

00:49:06.520 --> 00:49:14.679
And yeah, we're not trying to unify everything for end users, but we're just trying to address

00:49:14.679 --> 00:49:21.479
the much smaller problem of how can people write data frame agnostic tools. Thank you.

00:49:23.959 --> 00:49:27.560
Oh yeah. So yeah, Barrett gives a nice comment about that in the chat saying that they were

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:31.800
able to reduce the number of interfaces by just integrating Narwhals. And before they had to

00:49:31.800 --> 00:49:37.000
write adapters manually, and now there's just a single interface. What you see with a lot of

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:44.199
data frame consuming tools is that the kind of things they're doing with data frames, it's

00:49:44.199 --> 00:49:49.479
it's a lot more limited compared to what end users are doing with data tools. So there,

00:49:49.479 --> 00:49:51.399
I think it is feasible to bring things together.

