to chat about with us today, Marco, or something that you're really excited about

00:53:43.080 --> 00:53:47.080
that we haven't got a chance to cover? Okay, yeah. Well, there was just a comment

00:53:47.080 --> 00:53:52.199
about map elements in Polars. So map elements is the way that you can apply user-defined functions

00:53:52.199 --> 00:53:59.560
row by row. And it's really a last resort function. It's something you should only use

00:53:59.560 --> 00:54:06.439
if you absolutely have to. Usually it's just more efficient to use the built-in expressions API

00:54:06.439 --> 00:54:11.479
or to write a plugin if you really need to. But regarding map elements, one of the most fun

00:54:11.479 --> 00:54:16.679
experiences I've had in open source was when I just got so angry seeing some blog posts where

00:54:16.679 --> 00:54:22.120
people were saying, ah, Polars, it's not really faster than Pandas because look at this function

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:26.840
where I used map elements and it's not very fast. I was like, okay, there needs to be a way

00:54:27.879 --> 00:54:33.399
to tell people not to use map elements. So my first suggestion was to rename it

00:54:33.399 --> 00:54:38.360
to map elements underscore slowly, but this got rejected.

00:54:40.040 --> 00:54:44.760
I'm not really sure why. I think it was a brilliant name, but no, it didn't happen.

00:54:46.439 --> 00:54:51.159
So what we then did was we would take the lambda function which people pass in,

00:54:51.719 --> 00:54:59.000
we decompose the bytecode, we reverse engineer the bytecode to figure out what the user had

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:03.639
passed in, and then we can emit a warning telling the user what to do instead.

00:55:04.919 --> 00:55:11.000
And yeah, that was wild. Most fun, one of the most fun open source experiences ever.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:15.639
We can't do it for everything. If we could, then we could just do it for them

00:55:15.639 --> 00:55:20.679
instead of emitting a warning. And I really don't want to do it for the user in cases

00:55:20.679 --> 00:55:26.360
when we can detect it because then people don't learn. So yeah, we emit the warning

00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:28.199
instead of doing it for you to teach you a lesson.

